  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What does a flashing folder with question mark mean on a Macbook?",
  "response": "A flashing folder with a question mark on a MacBook typically indicates that the computer is unable to find the startup disk or operating system. This can happen for several reasons, including:\n\n1. **Incorrect Startup Disk Selection:** The startup disk may not be properly selected. This can happen if you recently changed settings or connected new storage devices.\n\n2. **Disk Issues:** There might be an issue with the hard drive or SSD. It could be physically damaged, or there might be filesystem corruption.\n\n3. **Missing or Corrupted System Files:** Essential system files needed to boot up might be missing or corrupted.\n\nTo troubleshoot and potentially fix the issue:\n\n1. **Restart the MacBook:** Sometimes a simple restart can resolve temporary issues.\n\n2. **Check Startup Disk Selection:**\n   - Turn off your MacBook.\n   - Turn it back on and immediately press and hold the Option (\u2325) key.\n   - This will bring up the Startup Manager, allowing you to select the correct startup disk.\n\n3. **Reset NVRAM/PRAM:**\n   - Turn off your MacBook.\n   - Turn it back on and immediately press and hold Option + Command + P + R.\n   - Hold these keys for about 20 seconds, then release.\n\n4. **Disk Utility:**\n   - Boot into Recovery Mode by restarting and holding Command (\u2318) + R.\n   - Select Disk Utility from the macOS Utilities window.\n   - Use Disk Utility to check and repair the startup disk.\n\n5. **Reinstall macOS:**\n   - Boot into Recovery Mode (Command + R).\n   - Select \"Reinstall macOS\" from the macOS Utilities window.\n   - Follow the on-screen instructions to reinstall the operating system.\n\n6. **Seek Professional Help:** If none of the above steps work, there could be a more serious hardware issue. It may be necessary to visit an Apple Store or authorized service provider for further diagnosis and repair.\n\nBackup your data regularly to minimize the impact of such issues on your data integrity.",
